a variety of reasons However, in further discussion from the WALS page on the absence of ‘th’ sounds, the fact that English does have ‘th’ whereas Cantonese doesn’t is not unusual geographically. There appears to be no geographical pattern to the presence or absence of ‘th,’ as we see that many languages near England don’t have ‘th’ whereas near the origin of Cantonese there is also the Lakkia language that does indeed have the ‘th’ sound. %0a%3c %0a%3c A curious aspect that I would like to note is that there is a differentiation between Cantonese and Hong Kong Cantonese in PHOIBLE. Additionally, WALS notes an interest aspect which is that the ‘th’ sound might arise from the loss of sibilant qualities from /s/ and /z/, which happens in only some varieties of Yue Chinese or Cantonese but not in Hong Kong Cantonese. I’m curious how within the language did this differentiation occur? A possibility that comes immediately to mind would be the British colonization of Hong Kong, and thus use of English, where the ‘th’ sound does appear. However, it is hard to say without additional research whether this is by causation or an unusual coincidence. %0a%3c %0a%3c Sources: %0a%3c https://wals.info/chapter/19%0a%3c https://wals.info/feature/19A#2/19.3/152.9 %0a%3c https://phoible.org/inventories/view/19 %0a%3c https://phoible.org/inventories/view/2309 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c You must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c 